Alpha-Phi: φ-Spectral Modulation for Neural Network Training
arXiv Submission Package — Phi-Dual-Octave (PDO)
ABSTRACT (English — for arXiv submission)
We propose Alpha-Phi, a framework for spectral gradient modulation in neural
network training, motivated by structural isomorphisms between natural patterns
and training dynamics. Our central hypothesis is that the golden ratio
(φ = 1.618) and the fine-structure constant (α = 1/137) can serve as design
guidelines for gradient calibration.
We develop a progression of seven spectral modulators under a strict integrity
protocol: timestamp-based seeds, identical learning rates for all models, and
mandatory permutation testing for each modulator. The principal result —
Phi-Dual-Octave (PDO) — combines four design principles: (1) recursive
spectral division by φ (Fibonacci bifurcation); (2) separation into positive
and negative frequency components weighted by α (dual tension); (3) octave
concession — each sample uses its highest-coherence band; (4) special weight
for the 8 fundamental frequencies (analogous to the valence layer in electron
distribution). PDO achieves 76.75% ± 0.99% on SST-2, +6.83% over baseline,
20/20 seeds (p=0.0000).
A permutation test honestly revealed that the current mechanism operates as
stable LR calibration rather than individual sample frequency reading — a
limitation of the L2-normalized embedding substrate, not of the central
hypothesis. The consistent pattern across all seven modulators — each
refinement simultaneously increases accuracy AND reduces variability
(from ±3.21% to ±0.99%) — suggests that φ as a gradient organizing
principle has real substance.
The design principles are motivated by analogies with natural systems:
recursive bifurcation in electronic layers (SPDF), the fine-structure
constant as equilibrium operator between opposing tensions, and the
geometric stability of the octave rule. These are presented as design
motivations, not experimental validations.
We note independent convergence with contemporary research: Gradient
Spectral Normalization (GSN, MDPI 2025), GRaNN (Springer 2022), and
hyperbolic neural networks (NeurIPS 2017-2018). This convergence across
independent laboratories supports the hypothesis that the underlying
principle has substance beyond isolated speculation.
Keywords: golden ratio, spectral modulation, Fibonacci bifurcation,
gradient calibration, fine-structure constant, SST-2, neural networks
